Introduction¶

The tmdb movie dataset description.¶

This report is aimed at performing data analysis on tmdb movie data set. This dataset contains 10000 movies with different informations.wa are going to analyse this dataset using numpy,pandas,and matplotlib and seaborn libraries.One or more questions will be asked and answered based on some of the attributes provided by this dataset include cast,genre, runtime, popularity,ratings, revenue, budget and so on.Below are the question to be answered by the information produced about this dataset.

Questions¶

  1. Which genre and production company has the most movie produced and most popularity from the 1960 to 2015.
  2. What is the average budget spent,revenue generated and profit made by each genres of movies over the years.
  3. Which genre are the highest in terms of budget,profit and revenue and popularity for each year from 1960 to 2015.
  4. what is relationship between revenue,profit and popularity and the relationship between runtime, revenue and budget.

def get_list(col_name):
    """
    Parameters
    ----------
    col_name : column 

    Return
    ----------
    a list of unique values in the column.

    """
    unique = list(dfm[col_name].unique())
    unique_list =[] #empty list to contain unique genres in the genres colums
    for j in range(len(unique)):
        y= unique[j]
        z= y.split('|')
        for text in range(len(z)):
            if z[text] not in unique_list:
                unique_list.append(z[text])
    return unique_list

def most_freq(col_name):
    """
    Parameters
    ----------
    col_name : the column we want to get.

    Returns
    -------
    unique_list : A list of unque element in the column in term of their fequency.

    """
     # to split the column and the add all the values in the genres 
     #colum to find the unique elements in the list and 
     #the number of time the occur using value_counts
    unique_list = pd.Series(dfp[col_name].str.cat(
        sep='|').split('|')).value_counts()
    return unique_list

QUESTION 3: Which genre are the highest in terms of budget,profit and revenue and popularity from year to year¶

To Answer this we define a function that groups our data by release year so we can get any of the columns we want.

In [34]:
def per_year(stat, col):
    """
    Parameters
    ----------
    stat : statistics to be 
    perform by the agg function(either max or sum).
    sort_col : column we want to get for each year.

    Returns
    ----------
    A barchart with most sort_col for each year

    """
    per_year = df_exploded[['release_year', col, 'genres', ]].sort_values(['release_year', col],
                                                                               ascending=False)
    # to get the best profit for each year after grouping by release year
    per_year = pd.DataFrame(per_year.groupby(['release_year'], as_index=False).agg({col: [stat],
                                                                                    'genres': ['first']}))

    # The next three lines are to get the list of value in each of the three columns
    v = [i for i in per_year.iloc[:, 0]]
    w = [i for i in per_year.iloc[:, 1]]
    x = [i for i in per_year.iloc[:, -1]]
   
    # to crate a new dataframe from the per_year dataframe 
    #so that no column with be multindexed. 
    df_new = pd.DataFrame({'year': v, col: w, 'genres': x})
    print(df_new.genres.value_counts())
    #to plot barchart using matplotlib pyplot
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(12, 7) )
    hbars = ax.bar(df_new.year, df_new[col], align='center',width =0.5)
    ax.bar_label(hbars, labels=df_new.genres,
                 rotation=90, padding=10, fontsize=12.5)
    ax.set_title(f' Genre with the most {col} for each year'.title())
    ax.set_xlabel('year'.title(), fontsize=15)
    ax.set_ylabel(col.title(), fontsize=15)
    # To setup the figure size.
    sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(10,5)})
    sns.set_style("darkgrid")

Question 4: relationship between revenue,profit and popularity and relationship between runtime, revenue and budget.¶

we are going to use framework of linear regression statistical models to estimate a simple relationship between these movie attributes using the seaborn Regplot..

In [39]:
def plot_rel(col_a,col_b) : 
    """
    Parameters
    ----------
    col_a: first column
    col_b : second column.

    Returns
    ----------
    A scatter chart showing the correlation between col_a and col_b

    """
        
    import statsmodels.api as sn
    import scipy  
    #To get the statistacal correlation tbetween the two columns
    print(f'correlation between {col_a} and {col_b} is' , scipy.stats.pearsonr(df[col_a],df[col_b])[0])
    sns.set_theme(color_codes=True)
    #To plot a scatter chart
    sns.regplot(x=col_a, y= col_b, data=dfp, marker="+", 
                scatter_kws={"s": 50 });
    sns.set(rc={'figure.figsize':(7,5)})
    plt.xlabel(col_a.title(), fontsize=12)
    plt.ylabel(col_b.title(), fontsize=12);
    plt.title(f'relationship between {col_a} and {col_b}'.title(), fontsize=12);
    
    #print('correlation between col_a and col_b is' , scipy.stats.pearsonr(df[col_a],df[col_b])[0])

  2. PLOT 2 shows the relationship between popularity and revenue.There is apositive correlation between them which is aproximately 0.67 which means the their is a tendency to generate more revenue with increasing popularity.
  3. PLOT 3 shows that the correlation between runtime and budget is 0.22 which means that movie runtime might not affect budget.
  4. PLOT 4 shows that the correlation between budget and revenue is 0.73. which means movies with high budget tends to generate high revenue.

Conclusion¶

For movie directors and production companies more profit will be amde from producing genres with high average popularity such as Adventure, Action and Drama. this is because there is a high correlation between popularity and profit. Therefore,the more popular the movie, the more the revenue and profit.
Also, universal pictures, warner bros and paramount pictures have produced the most movie from 1960 to 2015.
Limitations¶

Almost 56% of the values in the runtime and revenue and profit values were zero which not valid for this columns so I had to replace them with the mean of each column which might have affected the result of the analysis.

Also the Analysis result might show unintentional bias because our 1000 rows were dropped as a result of missing values and null values. there is a possibility that this might skew our result.
